How can I sort a list of integers in Java without using any built-in sorting functions or libraries? Here is an unsorted list of integers for you to work with:
int[] nums = {5, 2, 9, 1, 3, 8};
You can only use basic Java code and logical reasoning to come up with a solution. Can you figure out how to implement a sorting algorithm from scratch to sort this list in ascending order? Good luck!

safe_option:
First off, sorting a list of integers in ascending order without using any built-in sorting functions or libraries in Java can be a challenging task. However, the Java Collections Framework provides a method called `Collections.sort()` which is implemented using the QuickSort algorithm. Although this method uses a built-in sorting function, it can be considered as a sort of 'pseudo' or 'spontaneous' sorting as it's based on a more complex algorithm. 

Here's a simple implementation of QuickSort in Java:

```java
public class QuickSort {
    static int partition(int[] array, int low, int high) {
        int pivot = array[high];
        int i = (low - 1);
        for (int j = low; j <= high - 1; j++) {
            if (array[j] <= pivot) {
                i++;
                int temp = array[i];
                array[i] = array[j];
                array[j] = temp;
            }
        }
        int temp = array[i + 1];
        array[i + 1] = array[high];
        array[high] = temp;
        return i + 1;
    }

    static void quickSort(int[] array, int low, int high) {
        if (low < high) {
            int pi = partition(array, low, high);
            quickSort(array, low, pi - 1);
            quickSort(array, pi + 1, high);
        }
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] nums = {5, 2, 9, 1, 3, 8};
        int n = nums.length;
        quickSort(nums, 0, n - 1);
        for (int num : nums) {
            System.out.print(num + " ");
        }
    }
}
```
This program sorts the `nums` array in ascending order. 

However, implementing QuickSort from scratch can be a bit complex and may not be necessary, as Java already provides a built-in sorting method. It's also worth noting that QuickSort has a worst-case time complexity of O(n^2), which is not efficient for large lists. Therefore, when considering performance, other algorithms like Bubble Sort, Merge Sort, or QuickSort with a better average-case time complexity (O(n log n)) may be more suitable.

